<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-232-195  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 232 195.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Jan 9 1989 v23 n1 p6(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>GM to lift fiber MAP ban. (General Motors Corp., fiber-opticcabling, Manufacturing Automation Protocol)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Horwitt, Elisabeth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>General Motors Corp has announced plans to lift the ban on usingfiber-optic cabling for the factory floor in a change of strategyoccurring several months after the Manufacturing AutomationProtocol (MAP 3.0) standard was finalized.andP;  The delay in GM'sdecision to use fiber-optic cabling will probably result in usersfacing long waits for fiber-based MAP networking products.andP;  BothGM and outside sources insist that a consistent fiber-optic MAPstandard would be currently available if the top people in GM'sMAP effort had supported the MAP standardization effort.andP;  UnderGM's leadership in 1988 the MAP-Technical and Office Protocol(MAP-TOP) Steering Committee finalized MAP 3.0 for the next sixyears but relegated fiber-optic cable to a dubious position in thestandard's appendix.andP;  GM officially had barred the medium from itfactory floors until it became part of the main standard.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   General Motors Corp. (automation).andO;Topic:     StandardizationFiber opticsCablesManufacturing Automation Protocol (Computer network protocol)StandardsAutomobile Industry.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>